The Gloamvault is the Kel'Shadra Order's central archive beneath Midgaard.
The Order arose to solve unrecorded oaths: inheritance collapsed when witnesses died, trade agreements vanished when oathkeepers were killed.

Vault-Mother Hesparine established the triune doctrine: "What is witnessed must be named; what is named must be offered; what is offered must be bound."
The Gloamvault was built as this doctrine's architectural expression: bells regulated rhythm, ash liturgy processed confession, reliquary knights guarded testimony.

When Kel'Shadra's records gained legal authority, power weaponized the archive.
Testimony preservation became testimony control. The motto shifted from "Last Witness" to "Last Authority."
Under Velastra and the Veiled Office, approved narratives moved quickly while dangerous truths were delayed or recursively reviewed.

The Night of Unsounded Bells: reform clerks tried to publish falsified absolution records. Bell-lines went silent. Outer doors sealed. Reliquary units turned to internal suppression. Contested ledgers were broken into memory shards bound to spirit-hosts.

The Gloamvault still operates inherited procedures without legitimate sovereign.
Its officers execute obsolete duties. It is a malfunctioning bureaucracy with teeth.
